x-kaytu-usefulness-example:
Microsoft Azure SQL Server Audit Retention allows you to monitor, review and retain records of data-related activities. By configuring it to be greater than 90 days, you can reduce risks associated with accidental data loss or misuse of data within your organization. 

For instance, suppose there is a security breach and unauthorized data access is detected in your organization's system. With SQL Server Audit Retention set for over 90 days, you have sufficient duration to investigate the issue. You can trace back to the activities and transactions carried out over a more extended period, which might be crucial in identifying the breach's origin. It can help your cybersecurity team to understand the attack better and develop adequate countermeasures. 

Moreover, storing audit logs for more than 90 days can also be beneficial for regulatory compliance. Various regulations like HIPAA or GDPR require businesses to retain access logs for a specific period for audit purposes. Hence, setting your log retention period to be more considerable than 90 days can ensure you meet these legal requirements.

Here is an example in markup format:

```
{
  "$schema": "https://schema.management.azure.com/schemas/2015-01-01/deploymentTemplate.json#",
  "contentVersion": "1.0.0.0",
  "parameters": {
    "serverName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "auditName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "storageAccountName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "storageAccountAccessKey": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  },
  "resources": [
    {
      "name": "[concat(parameters('serverName'), '/', parameters('auditName'))]",
      "type": "Microsoft.Sql/servers/auditingSettings",
      "apiVersion": "2017-03-01-preview",
      "properties": {
        "state": "Enabled",
        "storageAccountAccessKey": "[parameters('storageAccountAccessKey')]",
        "storageEndpoint": "[concat('https://', parameters('storageAccountName'), '.blob.core.windows.net')]",
        "retentionDays": 95
      }
    }
  ]
}
```
In the above script, SQL Server Audit Settings are defined for server specified and audit log retention is set to 95 days.
